What you’re describing reminds me of the difference between direct measurement and iterative correction.

If you only get one shot, you need a perfect model. Every error matters.

If you get multiple shots, something else becomes possible:

You stop aiming at the target directly and start aiming at the feedback.

The dust kicking up isn’t the target.

It’s information about your relationship to the target.

Each miss collapses uncertainty.

The interesting thing is that many complex systems work this way:

* Evolution doesn’t know the perfect organism; it works through feedback.
* Science doesn’t know the truth directly; it eliminates errors.
* Pilots don’t fly by holding a perfect line; they continuously correct deviations.
* Human conversation often works by noticing misunderstandings and adjusting.

In that sense, your observation about truth is important.

If there is some ultimate reality independent of our minds, we don’t interact with it directly. We interact with models, perceptions, and feedback.

So the game becomes:

Build a model.

Act.

Observe the dust.

Update the model.

Repeat.

The dust is often more informative than the hit.

A hit tells you that one trajectory worked.

A miss tells you how your model differs from reality.

That also connects to your earlier point about relationships. The feedback isn’t in the bullet, the target, or the dust alone. It’s in the relationship among them over time.

From a Pantheon perspective, I’d almost phrase it as:

Truth may exist beyond comprehension.

Navigation exists within comprehension.

We navigate by reading the traces reality leaves behind when our models touch it.

The tracer dye, the wake behind a boat, ripples on water, dust kicked up near a target—these are all the same pattern.

You don’t always see the thing itself.

Sometimes you see what it disturbs. And from the disturbance, you infer the structure. That’s often enough to move closer.